181
00:08:03,851 --> 00:08:06,353 line:-2
Let's get started by
talking about System Extensions.


182
00:08:06.386 --> 00:08:08.021 line:-2 align:center
System Extensions
allow for software


183
00:08:08,055 --> 00:08:10,657 line:-2
like network extensions
and endpoint security solutions


184
00:08:10.691 --> 00:08:12.392 line:-2 align:center
to extend the functionality
of macOS


185
00:08:12.426 --> 00:08:15.095 line:-2 align:center
without requiring
kernel-level access.


186
00:08:15,128 --> 00:08:17,431 line:-2
We've made a few changes
to the System Extension payload


187
00:08:17.464 --> 00:08:19.099 line:-2 align:center
to enhance
the management experience.


188
00:08:19.132 --> 00:08:22.970 line:-2 align:center
In macOS 11.3, installing
the System Extension payload


189
00:08:23.003 --> 00:08:24.938 line:-2 align:center
changes the state
of a system extension.


190
00:08:24.972 --> 00:08:26.807 line:-2 align:center
For example,
if a system extension


191
00:08:26,840 --> 00:08:28,275 line:-1
is pending user approval,


192
00:08:28.308 --> 00:08:30.944 line:-2 align:center
installing the payload
will activate the extension.


193
00:08:30.978 --> 00:08:32.713 line:-2 align:center
Conversely,
removing the payload will now


194
00:08:32,746 --> 00:08:34,681 line:-2
deactivate
the system extension.


195
00:08:34,715 --> 00:08:37,317 line:-2
In macOS Monterey,
there is a new feature


196
00:08:37,351 --> 00:08:39,453 line:-1
called RemovableSystemExtension.


197
00:08:39.486 --> 00:08:41.255 line:-2 align:center
This will allow an app
to deactivate


198
00:08:41,288 --> 00:08:42,890 line:-1
its own system extension,


199
00:08:42.923 --> 00:08:45.826 line:-2 align:center
for example,
when the app uninstalls itself.


200
00:08:45,859 --> 00:08:48,962 line:-2
With this feature, there will be
no admin password required


201
00:08:48.996 --> 00:08:50.898 line:-1 align:center
to remove the system extension.


202
00:08:50,931 --> 00:08:52,499 line:-2
This may
be useful in deployments


203
00:08:52,533 --> 00:08:55,035 line:-1
where the Mac has no admin user.


204
00:08:55.068 --> 00:08:57.404 line:-2 align:center
In macOS Big Sur,
it became a requirement


205
00:08:57.437 --> 00:09:00.140 line:-2 align:center
to reboot a Mac to modify
kernel extensions.


206
00:09:00.174 --> 00:09:01.909 line:-2 align:center
We've added
a few features to make


207
00:09:01.942 --> 00:09:03.944 line:-2 align:center
managing kernel
extensions easier.


208
00:09:03.977 --> 00:09:07.314 line:-2 align:center
First, we added an option
to the RestartDevice command


209
00:09:07.347 --> 00:09:08.782 line:-1 align:center
that tells the Mac to rebuild


210
00:09:08,815 --> 00:09:10,918 line:-2
its kernel extension cache
on reboot.


211
00:09:10,951 --> 00:09:13,086 line:-2
This is required anytime
a kernel extension


212
00:09:13.120 --> 00:09:15.022 line:-1 align:center
is added or removed.


213
00:09:15,055 --> 00:09:18,492 line:-2
Use the optional KextPaths
key to specify kernel extensions


214
00:09:18.525 --> 00:09:20.861 line:-2 align:center
that haven't been discovered
by the operating system.


215
00:09:20.894 --> 00:09:23.030 line:-2 align:center
This allows
MDM to install an app


216
00:09:23,063 --> 00:09:25,499 line:-2
and load the kernel
extension without requiring


217
00:09:25,532 --> 00:09:27,968 line:-2
the user to launch
the app before rebooting.


218
00:09:28,001 --> 00:09:30,637 line:-2
The new NotifyUser
option will allow MDM


219
00:09:30.671 --> 00:09:33.006 line:-2 align:center
to display a reboot
notification to the user.


220
00:09:33.040 --> 00:09:34.675 line:-2 align:center
When clicked,
the user can perform


221
00:09:34,708 --> 00:09:36,743 line:-1
a graceful restart of the Mac.


222
00:09:36.777 --> 00:09:38.745 line:-2 align:center
The NotifyUser feature
can be used outside


223
00:09:38.779 --> 00:09:40.581 line:-2 align:center
of the context of kernel
extensions,


224
00:09:40,614 --> 00:09:43,116 line:-2
but it's especially helpful
when they're combined.


225
00:09:43,150 --> 00:09:45,319 line:-2
The AllowNonAdminUserApprovals
key


226
00:09:45,352 --> 00:09:47,855 line:-2
in the System Policy
Kernel Extensions payload


227
00:09:47,888 --> 00:09:50,257 line:-2
allows a standard user
to complete the installation


228
00:09:50,290 --> 00:09:51,825 line:-1
of kernel extensions.


229
00:09:51.859 --> 00:09:55.128 line:-2 align:center
Note the user must
perform the restart from within


230
00:09:55.162 --> 00:09:57.798 line:-2 align:center
System Preferences
or use the notification


231
00:09:57.831 --> 00:10:01.535 line:-2 align:center
from MDM to trigger
the kernel cache rebuild.


232
00:10:01,568 --> 00:10:04,204 line:-2
Depending on the hardware,
you may need a bootstrap token


233
00:10:04.238 --> 00:10:05.606 line:-1 align:center
to complete this step.


234
00:10:05.639 --> 00:10:07.174 line:-2 align:center
You can find out
if this is required


235
00:10:07,207 --> 00:10:09,276 line:-1
in the SecurityInfo query.


236
00:10:09,309 --> 00:10:11,812 line:-1
Next, let's talk about apps.


237
00:10:11,845 --> 00:10:14,281 line:-2
One of the coolest new features
of Mac computers


238
00:10:14,314 --> 00:10:17,451 line:-2
with Apple silicon
is the ability to run iPhone


239
00:10:17.484 --> 00:10:19.453 line:-1 align:center
and iPad apps.


240
00:10:19.486 --> 00:10:21.788 line:-2 align:center
With the initial launch
of macOS Big Sur,


241
00:10:21.822 --> 00:10:24.358 line:-2 align:center
we added a new DeviceInformation
query key


242
00:10:24.391 --> 00:10:26.193 line:-2 align:center
that reports if a Mac
supports iPhone


243
00:10:26.226 --> 00:10:27.861 line:-1 align:center
and iPad app installs,


244
00:10:27,895 --> 00:10:33,467 line:-2
and in macOS 11.3 on Apple
silicon, this now returns true.


245
00:10:33,500 --> 00:10:35,769 line:-2
Once you're ready to install
an App Store app


246
00:10:35,802 --> 00:10:37,571 line:-2
or your own
in-house enterprise app,


247
00:10:37,604 --> 00:10:39,039 line:-2
you'll need to include
a new flag


248
00:10:39.072 --> 00:10:40.707 line:-2 align:center
in the InstallApplication
command


249
00:10:40,741 --> 00:10:43,544 line:-2
to indicate that it's an iPhone
or iPad app.


250
00:10:43,577 --> 00:10:45,546 line:-2
And in the case
of in-house enterprise apps,


251
00:10:45,579 --> 00:10:49,449 line:-2
ensure the URL in the manifest
points directly to an .ipa file


252
00:10:49.483 --> 00:10:51.118 line:-1 align:center
and not a. pkg.


253
00:10:51,151 --> 00:10:52,886 align:center
We now support the ability
to manage


254
00:10:52,920 --> 00:10:54,922 line:0
iOS-style
provisioning profiles.


255
00:10:54.955 --> 00:10:56.990 line:-2 align:center
This feature allows
for independent management


256
00:10:57.024 --> 00:10:59.760 line:-2 align:center
of in-house enterprise apps
and provisioning profiles.


257
00:10:59.793 --> 00:11:01.962 line:-2 align:center
Now, let's talk about
some new features


258
00:11:01.995 --> 00:11:03.697 line:-1 align:center
exclusive to Apple silicon.


259
00:11:03,730 --> 00:11:05,599 line:-2
We are enhancing
the DeviceLock command


260
00:11:05,632 --> 00:11:08,135 line:-2
on Mac computers
with Apple silicon.


261
00:11:08,168 --> 00:11:11,071 line:-2
With this change, administrators
will now be able to send


262
00:11:11,104 --> 00:11:15,175 line:-2
a six-digit PIN, message,
and phone number to the device.


263
00:11:15.209 --> 00:11:17.644 line:-2 align:center
This will cause the Mac
to reboot and present the user


264
00:11:17,678 --> 00:11:19,279 line:-1
with the information provided,


265
00:11:19.313 --> 00:11:22.349 line:-2 align:center
bringing feature parity
across all Mac models.


266
00:11:22,382 --> 00:11:25,419 line:-2
With remote lock in place,
the user is unable to use


267
00:11:25,452 --> 00:11:27,521 line:-2
a Mac until the PIN
has been provided.


268
00:11:27,554 --> 00:11:29,723 line:-2
Once the PIN is entered,
the Mac will reboot


269
00:11:29.756 --> 00:11:32.826 line:-2 align:center
with all data intact
ready for login.


270
00:11:32,860 --> 00:11:34,461 line:-1
While this is a great start,


271
00:11:34,494 --> 00:11:37,664 line:-2
rebooting to recovery could
allow for unintended data access


272
00:11:37.698 --> 00:11:39.833 line:-2 align:center
or changing critical
security settings.


273
00:11:39.867 --> 00:11:43.470 line:-2 align:center
So we're adding a new feature
to set a recovery password.


274
00:11:43.504 --> 00:11:44.972 line:-1 align:center
The new SetRecoveryLock


275
00:11:45.005 --> 00:11:47.641 line:-2 align:center
and VerifyRecoveryLock
MDM commands


276
00:11:47,674 --> 00:11:50,043 line:-2
allow you to set
and verify a password


277
00:11:50,077 --> 00:11:51,678 line:-2
that must be entered
before the Mac


278
00:11:51.712 --> 00:11:53.814 line:-1 align:center
can reboot into recovery.


279
00:11:53,847 --> 00:11:55,782 line:-2
There are some important details
that you will want to know


280
00:11:55,816 --> 00:11:57,851 line:-1
about using these new commands.


281
00:11:57,885 --> 00:12:01,088 line:-2
The password can only
be set and removed by MDM.


282
00:12:01,121 --> 00:12:03,524 line:-2
Therefore,
if a user un-enrolls from MDM,


283
00:12:03.557 --> 00:12:06.527 line:-2 align:center
the recovery password
will be removed.


284
00:12:06,560 --> 00:12:09,530 line:-2
The MDM server needs
to know the existing password


285
00:12:09,563 --> 00:12:11,899 line:-1
to set a new password.


286
00:12:11.932 --> 00:12:14.468 line:-2 align:center
And finally,
both the DeviceLock PIN


287
00:12:14,501 --> 00:12:17,004 line:-2
and the Recovery Password
will be removed


288
00:12:17.037 --> 00:12:18.405 line:-1 align:center
when the Mac is erased.


289
00:12:18.438 --> 00:12:20.507 line:-2 align:center
Therefore, we recommend using
these features


290
00:12:20,541 --> 00:12:22,409 line:-2
in conjunction
with Activation Lock


291
00:12:22.442 --> 00:12:25.078 line:-2 align:center
to provide the best
security for your fleet.


292
00:12:25,112 --> 00:12:27,281 line:-2
Now, we know you're pretty
excited about these features,


293
00:12:27,314 --> 00:12:29,550 line:-1
but we do have one last thing.


294
00:12:29.583 --> 00:12:32.252 line:-2 align:center
Erase All Content and Settings
for the Mac.


295
00:12:32.286 --> 00:12:35.956 line:-2 align:center
New in macOS Monterey is
the ability to Erase All Content


296
00:12:35.989 --> 00:12:38.659 line:-2 align:center
and Settings
for a quick return to service.


297
00:12:38,692 --> 00:12:40,594 line:-2
And we're very excited
that this functionality


298
00:12:40,627 --> 00:12:43,664 line:-2
will be available
via MDM as well.


299
00:12:43.697 --> 00:12:45.866 line:-2 align:center
Sending the EraseDevice
command will now erase


300
00:12:45,899 --> 00:12:48,869 line:-2
all user data and reboot
back to Setup Assistant,


301
00:12:48,902 --> 00:12:51,038 line:-1
ready for the next user.


302
00:12:51,071 --> 00:12:52,439 line:-2
A couple of notes
on this feature


303
00:12:52.472 --> 00:12:54.408 line:-1 align:center
you'll want to be aware of:


304
00:12:55,809 --> 00:12:59,479 line:-2
This feature is supported on Mac
computers with Apple silicon


305
00:12:59,513 --> 00:13:03,283 line:-1
and the Apple T2 security chip.


306
00:13:03,317 --> 00:13:05,252 line:-2
If the Mac
has multiple partitions,


307
00:13:05.285 --> 00:13:08.255 line:-2 align:center
it will reboot back to setup
on the current system volume,


308
00:13:08,288 --> 00:13:11,725 line:-2
and all other volumes
will be erased.


309
00:13:11.758 --> 00:13:14.494 line:-2 align:center
On devices with Apple silicon,
this will also reset


310
00:13:14,528 --> 00:13:17,831 line:-2
any security settings that have
been modified in recovery.


311
00:13:17,865 --> 00:13:20,634 line:-2
We also know that you might not
want users to erase their Mac,


312
00:13:20.667 --> 00:13:23.136 line:-2 align:center
so we're bringing
the allowEraseContentAndSettings


313
00:13:23.170 --> 00:13:25.873 line:-1 align:center
restriction to the Mac.


314
00:13:25.906 --> 00:13:28.075 line:-2 align:center
We've covered
a ton of new features today,


315
00:13:28,108 --> 00:13:30,744 line:-2
and we're so excited for you
to get your hands on them.


